description:
This work presents a comprehensive critical commentary and systematic re-evaluation of the study &ldquo;  RNA innate immunity constitutes a barrier for interspecies chimerism  &rdquo; by Hu, Sun, Sakurai,  et al ., published in  Cell  (2025). The original article proposed a mechanistic model in which xenogeneic pluripotent stem cell (PSC)&ndash;derived RNA is sensed by host embryos through RIG-I&ndash;like receptor pathways, triggering antiviral innate immune activation that restricts donor-cell survival and thereby limits cross-species chimerism. Because the claims of this study have broad conceptual and translational implications&mdash;spanning developmental biology, immunology, synthetic embryology, and organoid-based xenogeneic chimera generation&mdash;rigorous post-publication scrutiny is essential. 
 This commentary provides a structured, section-by-section reassessment of the entire study, including conceptual framing, methodological execution, experimental design, statistical rigor, computational analysis, biological plausibility, and reproducibility. A dedicated figure-by-figure critique evaluates all main Figures 1&ndash;7, Extended Data Figures 1&ndash;15, and all Supplementary Figures. Particular attention is paid to issues of species-resolved transcriptomics, RNA structural immunogenicity, RLR pathway competence in preimplantation embryos, PSC culture-state heterogeneity, and the biological plausibility of antiviral signaling in early development. 
 The analysis identifies several major weaknesses that collectively undermine the central claims of the original paper: 

 lack of species-resolved mapping or lineage tracing, preventing unambiguous attribution of innate immune activation to host versus donor cells; 
 absence of biochemical assays demonstrating direct RIG-I/MDA5 engagement with donor RNA; 
 insufficient controls for RNA purity, dsRNA specificity, and transfection artefacts; 
 incomplete validation of CRISPR knockouts and limited chimerism rescue magnitudes; 
 highly variable and weak imaging signals, small sample sizes, and inconsistent quantification; 
 computational analyses that conflate transcriptomic divergence with immunogenic potential; and 
 biological implausibility of strong innate immune responses at preimplantation stages. 

 Taken together, our integrated synthesis concludes that the evidence provided in the original study does not convincingly support the assertion that RNA innate immunity forms a major barrier to interspecies chimerism. This commentary aims to enhance transparency, stimulate methodological rigor, and provide a framework for future investigations into the true mechanistic constraints governing xenogeneic chimera formation.

